{"id":8850,"date":"2017-12-14T09:22:33","date_gmt":"2017-12-14T17:22:33","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/?p=8850"},"modified":"2024-01-09T14:49:18","modified_gmt":"2024-01-09T22:49:18","slug":"macbeth-icefield-traverse","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/12\/14\/macbeth-icefield-traverse\/","title":{"rendered":"MACBETH ICEFIELD TRAVERSE"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><em>The MacBeth Icefield is easily accessible, flat and easy to traverse. The north access is up the north fork of Glacier Creek. The south access is the MacBeth Icefield trail. Shuttles are necessary. Glacier travel precautions are necessary &#8211; roped and have crevasse rescue capabilities.\u00a0<\/em><\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><em>It is best to camp at the north fork of Glacier Creek north access.\u00a0<\/em><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Location:<\/strong> north Glacier Creek\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Difficulty:\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Elevation gain:<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Key elevations:<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Distance:<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Time:<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Access:<\/strong> 2WD except the last access road to MacBeth Icefield Trail\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> <strong>Season:<\/strong> early July to October<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Map: 82K\/7 Duncan Lake\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Drive<\/strong>:<strong>\u00a0<\/strong>From the junction with road going south to Argenta, Johnson\u2019s Landing and Fry Creek Canyon. Zero odometer.\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>0.0<\/strong> Go straight on Duncan FSR, cross Hamill Creek in 200m and continue north along Duncan Lakes SE shore.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">9.2km Go straight. Left is the Glacier Creek Recreation Site. <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 9.7km Go right (NE) and ascend onto Duncan-Glacier Creek FSR. (left continues north along the Duncan Lake and River). 12.9km road is at creek level<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 14km Rainbow\u2019s End Ranch. Free-ranging animals. 18.1km cross a side creek.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">20.1km Junction. Go straight on the main road. (left is to the MacBeth Icefield TH). Place a shuttle vehicle here.\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 21.7km Cross Glacier Creek<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 33.7km After another bridged creek, junction. Go left (NW) up the north fork of Glacier Creek towards the Monica Meadows TH. Right (east) is to Jumbo Pass and Horseshoe Glacier.\u00a0Zero odometer. <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">0.0 Go NW up the north fork of Glacier Creek<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">1.7km Continue straight (NW) about 2kms to the road end at a washed-out bridge over Glacier Creek. (right (NE) goes uphill on Monica Road). Park and camp.\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Route\/Trail:<\/strong> North access: Cross the Glacier Creek on log jams upstream. Walk up the continuation of the N fork road, now very overgrown as it climbs up to the centre, a high point in the cutblock where there is a large old snag. In the trees, it is a moderate bushwhack staying to the ridge line heading NW. The ridge jogs left twice. At the second jog, cross onto the west side of the ridge and access the moraine. Walk NW gaining the glacier north of Mt MacDuff. Circle around MacDuff and climb the rocks to the right to access the neve. Rope up and cross the completely flat glacier heading due south for 3.5kms to the SW corner of MacBeth Icefield. Elevation gain is about 200&#8242; on the glacier. Mt Fleance is 1km to the west and Mt Banquo is 1km WSW of Fleance.\u00a0\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Descend heading for the east end of a tarn not marked on the map. Stay high heading for the ridge due south of the lake (cairn). Walk down the ridge until the cairns mark the trail on the west side of the ridge. The views of Graymalkin Falls and Lake are spectacular. Walk out the MacBeth Icefield Trail to the shuttle vehicle.\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The MacBeth Icefield is easily accessible, flat and easy to traverse. The north access is up the north fork of Glacier Creek. The south access is the MacBeth Icefield trail. Shuttles are necessary. Glacier travel precautions are necessary &#8211; roped &hellip; <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/12\/14\/macbeth-icefield-traverse\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"jetpack_post_was_ever_published":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_access":"","_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id":0,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content":false,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content":false,"footnotes":"","jetpac